\description{
Creates an undirected symmetric k-nearest neighbor (sKNN) graph from a numeric
data matrix. An edge between vertices \code{i} and \code{j} is present when either
\code{j} is among the \code{k} nearest neighbors of \code{i}, or \code{i} is among the \code{k}
nearest neighbors of \code{j}.
}
\details{
With no nearest-neighbor ties, the sKNN edge rule is equivalent to
\deqn{d_{ij} \le \max(\sigma_i, \sigma_j),}
where \eqn{\sigma_i} is the distance from point \eqn{i} to its \code{k}-th
non-self nearest neighbor.

If \code{connect.components = TRUE}, the graph is augmented with MST edges. The
default \code{connect.method = "component.mst"} first collapses each connected
component of the sKNN graph to one component vertex, weights each component
pair by the shortest data-space edge between them, and adds the minimum
spanning tree of this component graph. This adds exactly \code{m - 1} bridge
edges when the original sKNN graph has \code{m} connected components.
\code{connect.method = "component.mst.ann"} uses ANN nearest-neighbor bridge
candidates first and automatically falls back to exact component MST when
the sparse candidate graph does not connect all components. The alternative
\code{connect.method = "global.mst"} unions the sKNN graph with the full
Euclidean MST on the data points.

\code{neighbor.method = "exact"} computes all pairwise distances and is the
deterministic reference implementation. \code{neighbor.method = "ann"} uses
the bundled ANN kd-tree for the Euclidean kNN search step; exact parity can
differ only in nearest-neighbor tie cases. Edge weights are always returned
as ordinary Euclidean distances. Exact \code{component.mst} repair uses exact
pairwise bridge distances; \code{component.mst.ann} uses ANN bridge candidates
before guaranteed exact fallback.

If \code{prune.method = "local.geodesic"} or \code{prune.edges = TRUE}, an
experimental local-geodesic pruning stage is applied after the sKNN support
is built and before optional MST connectivity repair. Candidate edges are
processed longest-first. For an edge \verb{(i, j)}, the edge is removed only when
the currently retained graph contains an alternative path from \code{i} to \code{j},
restricted to the union of their local neighborhoods, whose length is at most
\code{prune.tau} times the direct edge length. \code{prune.method = "global.geodesic.ratio"} instead uses the whole graph as the alternative-path
search domain and removes long edges whose shortest alternative path is
within the configured geodesic-ratio threshold.
}
